r shows how corporate strategies have been shaped by twenty-first-century conditions—including globalization, economic decline, and the populism reflected in both the Trump and Sanders campaigns of 2016. Perhaps most important, Lafer shows that the corporate legislative agenda has come to endanger the scope of democracy itself. For anyone who wants to know what to expect from corporate-backed Republican leadership in Washington, D.C., there is no better guide than this record of what the same set of actors has been doing in the state legislatures under its control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBusiness and educationxUnited States. 0aBusiness and educationzUnited States. 0aBusiness and politicsxUnited States. 0aBusiness and politicszUnited States. 0aCorporate powerxUnited States. 0aCorporate powerzUnited States. 0aCorporationsxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aCorporationsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aJapanologistszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor policyxUnited States. 0aLabor policyzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aLabor unionszUnited States. 0aPolicy scienceszUnited Statesy20th century. 0aPostwar reconstructionzJapanxPlanning. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aconservative agenda, corporate agenda, corporate lobbies, economic wellbeing, working Americans, employee rights, government funding, American politics, public policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook p